### üîê Permissions and User Management (Linux CLI)

```bash
chmod +x <file>
```
Add execute permission to a file.

```bash
chmod 755 <file>
```
Set read, write, and execute for owner; read and execute for group and others.

```bash
chmod -R 755 <directory>
```
Recursively set permissions for a directory and its contents.

```bash
chown user:group <file>
```
Change ownership of a file or directory.

```bash
chown -R user:group <directory>
```
Recursively change ownership of a directory and its contents.

```bash
ls -l
```
View file permissions and ownership.

```bash
umask
```
Show default permission mask.

```bash
adduser <username>
```
Create a new user (Debian/Ubuntu).

```bash
useradd <username>
```
Create a new user (Red Hat/CentOS/Alpine style).

```bash
passwd <username>
```
Set or change a user's password.

```bash
deluser <username>
```
Delete a user (Debian/Ubuntu).

```bash
userdel <username>
```
Delete a user (Red Hat/CentOS/Alpine style).

```bash
usermod -aG <group> <username>
```
Add user to a group.

```bash
groups <username>
```
Show groups a user belongs to.

```bash
whoami
```
Display the current user.

```bash
id
```
Show UID, GID, and group info of the current user.
